this randomized controlled trial, we evaluated the efÔ¨Åcacy of dynamic measures (stroke volume change during passive leg raise) to guide resuscitation and improve patient outcome. RESEARCH QUESTION: Will resuscitation that is guided by dynamic assessments of Ô¨Çuid responsiveness in patients with septic shock improve patient outcomes? STUDY DESIGN AND METHODS: We conducted a prospective, multicenter, randomized clinical trial at 13 hospitals in the United States and United Kingdom. Patients presented

, multicenter, randomized clinical trial at 13 hospitals in the United States and United Kingdom. Patients presented to EDs with sepsis that was associated hypotension and anticipated ICU admission. Intervention arm patients were assessed for Ô¨Çuid responsiveness before clinically driven Ô¨Çuid bolus or increase in vasopressors occurred. Fluid resuscitation is a central component of septic shock treatment.1,2 Excessive Ô¨Çuid administration causes hypervolemia and is associated with tissue edema, organ dysfunction, increased ICU length of stay, prolonged ventilator dependence,3-5 and higher mortality rates.6-10 Guidelines recommend crystalloid Ô¨Çuid administration of at least 30 mL/kg for sepsis-induced tissue hypoperfusion or septic shock and suggest that ÔøΩ

kg for sepsis-induced tissue hypoperfusion or septic shock and suggest that ‚ÄúÔ¨Çuid administration beyond initial resuscitation requires careful assessment of the likelihood that the patient remains Ô¨Çuid responsive.‚Äù11 Robust evidence that supports this recommendation is lacking. Two-thirds of patients with septic shock demonstrate Ô¨Çuid overload on day 1, and Ô¨Çuid resuscitation often continues beyond the Ô¨Årst day of care.9-

ÔøΩÔøΩuid resuscitation often continues beyond the Ô¨Årst day of care.9-16 However, only one-half of septic patients will be Ô¨Çuid responsive and potentially beneÔ¨Åt from Ô¨Çuid administration.17-20 A propensity model analysis of 23,513 patients with sepsis demonstrated that day 1 Ô¨Çuid administration >5 L was associated with signiÔ¨Åcantly increased risk of death.8 Traditional methods of the

was associated with signiÔ¨Åcantly increased risk of death.8 Traditional methods of the assessment of Ô¨Çuid responsiveness (FR) such as vital signs, physical examination,21 and static measurements of circulatory pressure do not reliably correlate with FR.16 In contrast, dynamic measurement of stroke volume (SV) after an IV Ô¨Çuid bolus or passive leg raise (PLR) is a safe and feasible method of rapidly assessing the effectiveness of Ô¨Çuid-

PLR) is a safe and feasible method of rapidly assessing the effectiveness of Ô¨Çuid- induced augmentation of SV and cardiac output (CO).18,20,22-24 This approach has been associated with reduced length of stay, fewer postoperative complications, and earlier return to regular diet in surgical patients.25 A retrospective study of real-time, noninvasive bioreactance SV and cardiac performance measurements incorporated PLR to assess FR and guide resuscitation in patients with septic

SV and cardiac performance measurements incorporated PLR to assess FR and guide resuscitation in patients with septic shock in an ICU.23 Bioreactance analyzes the relative phase shift of an oscillating current passing through the thoracic cavity.26-30 Dynamic SV- guided resuscitation was associated with decreased net Ô¨Çuid balance, reduced ICU length of stay, risk of mechanical ventilation, time on vasopressors, and risk of renal replacement therapy (RRT) initiation

ventilation, time on vasopressors, and risk of renal replacement therapy (RRT) initiation.23 Given the uncertainty surrounding the beneÔ¨Åts of dynamic measure-guided Ô¨Çuid resuscitation, we designed the Fluid Responsiveness Evaluation in Sepsis- associated Hypotension (FRESH) Trial (NCT02837731). The primary objective was to determine if SV-guided dynamic assessment could guide the amount of IV Ô¨Çuid administered to patients with septic

-guided dynamic assessment could guide the amount of IV Ô¨Çuid administered to patients with septic shock. Methods Study Design We conducted a randomized unblinded clinical trial among adults with sepsis-associated hypotension to compare PLR-guided SV Take-home Points Study Question: Will resuscitation guided by dynamic assessments of Ô¨Çuid responsiveness in patients with septic shock improve patient outcomes? Results: In this multicenter randomized controlled trial of 124 patients with septic shock, treatment that

? Results: In this multicenter randomized controlled trial of 124 patients with septic shock, treatment that was guided by a dynamic assessment of Ô¨Çuid responsiveness (passive leg raise) compared with usual care resulted in a decreased Ô¨Çuid balance (0.65 L vs 2.02 L). Fewer patients required renal replacement therapy (5.1% vs 17.5%) or mechanical ventilation (17.7% vs 34.1%), and patients were more likely to be discharged

mechanical ventilation (17.7% vs 34.1%), and patients were more likely to be discharged home alive (63.9% compared with 43.9%). Interpretation: Personalized, dynamic Ô¨Çuid responsiveness monitoring enhances appropriate resuscitation Ô¨Çuid and vasopressors administration and improves patient outcomes. ressor management was used continuously during the intervention period (72 hours or ICU discharge, whichever occurred Ô¨Årst). An increase in SV $10% was considered FR. If the patient demonstrated FR, protocol prompts were provided to administer a crystalloid Ô¨Çuid bolus (500 mL) for persistent hypotension, with repeat PLRs after every Ô¨Çuid bolus. the patient was not FR, the initiation or up-titration of vasopressors was prompted with repeat PLRs after signiÔ¨Åcant escalation (an increase of 1 mg/kg/min norepinephrine).
